od%20%E2%80%94%20dare%20we%20say%2C%20edible%3F%20%E2%80%94%20considering%20the%20ordeal%20they%20went%20through.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nasa.gov%2Fmissions%2Fstation%2Fnasa-lets-ketchup-on-international-space-station-tomato-research%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epress%20release%20on%20Thursday%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20NASA%20shared%20a%20new%20image%20of%20what%20the%20rogue%20fruits%20looked%20like%20when%20they%20were%20found%2C%20reporting%20that%20they%20had%20become%20dehydrated%20and%20%26quot%3Bslightly%20squished.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BOther%20than%20some%20discoloration%2C%26quot%3B%20NASA%20said%2C%20they%20%26quot%3Bhad%20no%20visible%20microbial%20or%20fungal%20growth.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20tomatoes%20were%20grown%20on%20the%20International%20Space%20Station%20as%20part%20of%20NASA's%20VEG-05%20project%20which%20was%20launched%20late%20last%20year%20to%20study%20crop%20growth%2C%20food%20safety%2C%20and%20flavor%20in%20space.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20experiment%20used%20the%20space%20station's%20vegetable%20facility%20to%20grow%20dwarf%20tomatoes%2C%20lettuce%2C%20cabbage%2C%20kale%2C%20and%20flowers%2C%20in%20an%20effort%20to%20address%20the%20need%20for%20ongoing%20fresh%20food%20in%20space%20and%20on%20future%20missions%20to%20both%20the%20Moon%20and%20Mars%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nasa.gov%2Fmissions%2Fstation%2Fnasa-teams-persevere-through-plant-challenges-in-space%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eaccording%20to%20NASA%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20discovery%20of%20the%20long-lost%20tomatoes%20was%20announced%20earlier%20this%20month%20in%20a%20live-stream%20interview%20from%20the%20International%20Space%20Station.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%22768%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Frank%20Rubio%20smiles%20while%20gardening%20in%20space%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F657ba1e80ec98e92f74fcf8b%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22512%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3ENASA%20astronaut%20Frank%20Rubio%20was%20vindicated%20after%20his%20colleagues%20accused%20him%20of%20eating%20the%20missing%20tomatoes.%3Cp%3ENASA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20the%20experimental%20tomatoes%20were%20harvested%20in%20March%2C%20each%20astronaut%20was%20given%20a%20sample%20in%20a%20Ziplock%20bag%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.space.com%2Finternational-space-station-lost-tomato-frank-rubio-found%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ESpace.com%3C%2Fa%3E%20previously%20reported.%20The%20space-bound%20gardeners%20were%20instructed%20not%20to%20eat%20the%20fruit%20in%20case%20of%20potential%20fungal%20contamination.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERubio%2C%20however%2C%20soon%20lost%20track%20of%20his%20tomatoes%20while%20serving%20a%20record-breaking%20371%20days%20on%20the%20space%20station%20%E2%80%94%20leading%20to%20jabs%20from%20his%20fellow%20astronauts.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20embattled%20astronaut%20was%20finally%20exonerated%20earlier%20this%20month%20after%20having%20left%20the%20space%20station.%20The%20missing%20fruits%20were%20ultimately%20located%20in%20a%20plastic%20bag%2C%20NASA%20said.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20tomatoes%20will%20not%20be%20making%20a%20return%20voyage%20back%20to%20Earth%2C%20having%20already%20been%20discarded%2C%20according%20to%20NASA.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20plant%20research%20continues%20on%20the%20space%20station%20even%20in%20the%20aftermath%20of%20the%20case%20of%20the%20missing%20tomatoes.%20Scientists%20involved%20in%20the%20Plant-Habitat-03%20project%20are%20currently%20working%20to%20assess%20if%20genetic%20adaptions%20in%20a%20generation%20of%20plants%20grown%20in%20space%20are%20transferable%20to%20generations%20down%20the%20line%2C%20NASA%20said.%20The%20study's%20results%20could%20help%20researchers%20zero%20in%20on%20genetic%20elements%20in%20plants%20that%20make%20them%20adaptable%20to%20spaceflight%2C%20leading%20to%20the%20ability